1/3
Define "ideal." Do you mean for storytelling purposes, or do you mean in the real world in the foreseeable future, or...?

For storytelling purposes, for humans and anthros to meet requires explanation. The paleoanthropologists tell us that it looks like our ancestors exterminated all the rest of the hominids, every last one, down the last infant, before we even had agriculture or metal or the wheel. It is plausible to assume that they did this because the others were competitors for finite resources, and our ancestors won because they were just that much smarter, that much meaner, and that much better organized--and had they not been, they'd have gone extinct, and creatures descended from, say, Ardepithecus ramidus, would be having this discussion, perhaps making clicking sounds with their snouts as they typed. This strongly suggests that no world can be host to more than a single sophont species. I call this the Highlander Rule: there can be only one.

So if we're dropping humans and anthros into the same setting, the Highlander Rule casts an enormous shadow over the setting.

Maybe it's a fantasy story, set in a world where gods and magic are real. Okay, cat anthros are Bast's children, she made them, she protects them, and that's why they and we can coexist, that's fine, I guess, but we at least have to mention this, preferably by way of a viewpoint character walking past a temple of Bast and thinking to himself about it where the reader can see. If we want to set the story in more or less Current Year, though, we have to try a lot harder.

2/3
Aliens don't really work. There seem to be far too many ways for complex animals to exist for something from another world, one where conditions were probably not identical to those on Earth in every way, to look like anything we'd even recognize. There is an old sci-fi RPG that had an intelligent species who were basically wolf anthros, but they'd been created as an experiment by advanced ancient aliens a third of a million years prior to the setting's present, plopped down on a vaguely Earthlike planet a couple thousand light-years closer to the galactic core, and apparently abandoned and forgotten there, where they eventually figured out fire and the wheel and steam engines and spaceflight and faster-than-light travel on their own. This is maybe a stretch, but it's better than "UFOs land and sexy fox girls get out and say 'we need your seed, Earth man!'"

Sci-fi stories can have genetic engineering as the origin of anthros. Human nature suggests they'd probably have been created as living sex toys with no rights, which is depressing, but nothing else is very plausible. This is the only way I can see them coming into existence in the real world, too. This is, obviously, fraught with cultural and political implications that I do not care for a bit, and which go against the fun, carefree tone I'm hoping for.

3/3
Of all the possible authorial handwaves here, if we want there to be something more to it than "okay this world has humans and anthros just because, and the viewpoint character meets a wolf girl, and he asks her to awoo and she responds with an uwu instead..." the least painful, probably, at least for me, is that the anthros evolved on Earth in a parallel timeline that diverged from ours a very, very long time ago. The Highlander Rule says it's implausible that there would be more than a single intelligent species on that world. But maybe someone was using the Large Hadron Collider to warm up a his lunch and some kind of technomagical bullshit took place that opened portals between our world and theirs. And this is going to have to have been far enough in the past, in most instances, for first contact to have taken place and the two species learning one another's languages, trading, traveling back and forth, and all that. Otherwise we get ten chapters of the square-jawed human hero trying and failing to make the sounds an alien mouth and larynx can make, and trying to figure out a spoken language that has some components that are ultrasonic. It isn't really plausible that they'd step out of the portals speaking English with American newsreader accents, with a culture recognizable and familiar to us. This is an obstacle between the reader and the snoot boops and the floofy tails and the shenanigans at the skate park.
